narratives.question_text:
What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
(Your anonymous response to this question may be viewed by Yale College students, faculty, and advisers to aid in course selection and evaluating teaching.)
comments: basic information of statistics and how to interpret statistics in research

Learned how to conduct variety of statistical tests (one-sample z test, one-sample t test, independent samples ttest, paired samples t-test, correlation/linear regression, one-way ANOVA, two-way ANOVAs), learned how to use R to conduct statistical analysis, learned how to write up results in a research paper
Statistical thinking; how to use R.
different statistical tests
I learned a lot about statistics from two-way ANOVA testing to simple population means and was able to learn a lot about the new coding language R.

I learned about statistical concepts as well as how to run specific statistical tests (t-tests, correlation, regression, one-way ANOVA and two-way ANOVA). I learned how to absorb and comprehend statistics from articles.
Great foundational knowledge of statistics and applications in social science.

Thorough overview of the applicable statistical concepts and tests for psychology. Samples, populations, z- and t-tests, independent and paired samples t-tests, and ANOVAs. I appreciated that enough detail was provided to understand the general concept without things getting too complex. I feel pretty much 100% prepared now for any psych paper I read.

This course taught me the fundamentals of how to use R for statistics and how to analyze data to see if it correlated or significant. I also learned a lot about samples vs population, types of variables, different statistical analysis, and how to write a statistical report.
how to code in R and do statistical tests and analysis
working knowledge of R and psych stats
I was able to gain an introductory  understanding of statistics and using R.
R, stats knowledge

I learned the basics of statistical analysis for psychology using R, how to perform and recognize various statistical tests, and how to write up professional reports of findings. This course was super helpful for completing other upper division psych/cog sci courses I had this semester, and helped me analyze and interpret my own data from personal projects.
Not as easy before, you definitely need to put in the work. Take S&DS230 instead.
Statistical analysis and evaluation of source validity
I learned the basics of statistics and how to perform some introductory coding with R.
Learned how to use R and do basic statistical tests. Also learned good critical thinking skills regarding statistics and significance.
I learned about ANOVA's, R Studio, and the different tests available for statistical study
Learn the basics of coding in R, learn how to perform statistical analyses, develop understanding of important concepts in statistics
Statistics
I learned the basic concepts of statistics as well as the basics of R programming, which is an important tool for a lot of statistical analysis in psychology.
I learned basic R coding (arithmetic, making diagrams, modifying info in dataframes) and a wide range of statistical tests
Statistical evaluations in R Studio
the basics of stats and how to run/write a simple report with statistical data analysis
I learned both how to use r for data analysis as well as how to read and understand statistical language/results in the context of research papers.
The basics of gathering and working with data, and how to work with the program R.
I learned significant insight in the field of statistics, as well as a better understanding of R.
I learned about how to read, visualize, and analyze data. I learned about different tests that can be conducted in order to analyze such data.
I learned basic statistics and how they can apply to psychological research
I learned about the application of stats in psychology. We learned how to use basic R
I gained an introduction to analyzing statistical data and how to use R
I learned how to use R. I learned how to perform statistical tests to discover significant or non significant results. I learned how to write up statistical data.
I learned all the fundamental concepts for statistics in the social sciences. Also developed my critical thinking skills and became a better and more savyy consumer of statistics found in the media
foundational knowledge of statistics, familiarity with R, confidence in choosing tests & analyzing/reporting results

narratives.question_text:
What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
(Your anonymous response to this question may be viewed by Yale College students, faculty, and advisers to aid in course selection and evaluating teaching.)
comments: organized and well-explained topics, provides intro experience to R which was great
R is intimidating at first, but the teaching team is very supportive. EdDiscussion was also a great forum for peer learning.
clear lectures and easy to follow lectures helped organize the material
I found no weaknesses with this course, and I loved the pacing and how it kept all of the students engaged while also challenging us on an intellectual level.

Strengths: Very manageable workload, Ilker is a great professor, and the material is practical and interesting!
Weaknesses: I didn't get as comfortable with R (the coding language) as much as I would have liked to

strengths: clear lectures and the teaching team was very responsive to questions
weaknesses: the homeworks and labs did not prepare us well for the midterm and final, lectures were just ok I'd say

Strengths: thorough PowerPoint slides presented well by the professor; lab sections each week were pretty good and the lab keys and homework keys provided were helpful. R is a good platform for learning but might be difficult for beginners.

Weaknesses: R is strange at times and seems unnecessary for some simpler concepts.

The class presented a lot of important material, however, I felt that it was poorly adjusted for virtual learning. The first exam set-up was a bit tragic with a confusing organization. This was fixed for the second exam but it was still not optimally adjusted. Additionally, going through labs while on zoom should have been recorded. I understand that attendence in section was mandatory and therefore section was not recorded, but there was so much content covered during the labs and I and various other students had a hard time keeping up with having the screen being shared as well as trying to run R studio. It was a lot to handle on one device.
i did not like the teaching style. the professor went through the lecture way too fast and didn't really teach, he only read off of the slides.
consistent workload and learning, the exams were terrible though

In terms of homework and projects, the class was straightforward. However, I think the exams are what made this course very difficult. The amount of questions we were expected to answer in the duration of just 50 minutes led me to not completely finish any of the exams, which caused me a lot of anxiety and stress.
Good lectures and slides.

This course was organized very well, with many resources available. I liked using EdDiscussion to get questions answered outside of class, and the TFs and professor were very helpful and knowledgeable. The one thing that I did not like was the first exam format on Qualtrics, but the teaching team took the classes' feedback and changed the format for the second exam.
i think that sometimes lectures could have used the entire 75 minutes instead of 50; sometimes content was rushed through or underexplained. but overall i think i learned a lot from the class
I think both the lecture content and lab/discussion sections are structured well, but I think the connection between the two could be improved to help facilitate overall learning and growth.
Really clear and organized, clear expectations.

Strengths: easy to follow and understand, passionate about statistics Weaknesses: went a bit too slow at times (too much time on mean, median, and mode); required attendance for live lectures, which would make me disengage and just watch recorded lectures later anyway

The lectures were extremely fast-paced, especially for an introductory course. The lecture format of the course made it very hard to comprehend the material and follow along. In addition, we utilized the programming language known as "R" but it was mostly used for problem sets and barely included on exams. Exams were extremely hard to prepare for since the problem sets were very unrelated to how the exams were formatted.

Strengths: very well-taught, TFs always available for questions and very supportive, highly engaging lectures with a strong live component, challenging problem sets that made students engage more with the material
Weaknesses: extremely strict grade cutoffs, Sunday night problem sets and no office hours over the weekend to help with questions, some TFs clearly more engaged with the course and more dedicated to students than others
More leinancy with attendance
The course was very easy to follow and lectures, slides, announcements, etc. were all posted very promptly and regularly.

Strengths: great teaching team, manageable workload, and lots of support systems (office hours, Edpuzzle discussion threads). Weaknesses: disorganized material (oftentimes lecture recordings were not uploaded to a single space and there were inconsistencies in the notes)
The lectures were well taught and understandable. More time for the exams would have been appreciated.

I think the course was organized very well with clear mechanisms to get help if you needed it. I really like how many modes there were of getting help such as ed discussion, office hours, and individual meetings. I do not think that the course had any weaknesses really... I had made a note about including cc in lectures during the course evaluations which was promptly included which indicated to me that the professor and TFs were really invested in our learning and interested in our feedback.
Its taught in a very straightforward way and the section is actually very useful for the homework. Lecture slides can be hard to follow sometimes though.

The strength of the course was the PSETs which greatly helped to clarify some of the concepts, as well as the detailed lecture slides. However, the lack of practice test questions made it difficult, but I believe that was only due to the fact that the course changed to R.

This course was super organized and the TFs were very kind and helpful. An area of improvement could be allowing more collaborative work in breakout rooms in order to increase engagement and allow peers to interact with each other!

Strengths: relevant material, incredibly kind and supportive teaching staff
Weaknesses: this class could have benefitted from being graded on a curve. the average scores for midterms hovered around the 80s but you still had to get over a 93% to get an A

strengths: its a good introduction to R and stats

weakness: I would have liked more practice problems for the exams. I didn't find the two course for R really helpful
The class was well structured and provides an introduction to concepts if you don't have a statistics background.

Strengths: Professor is very clear and direct. TFs are very knowledgeable. Communication is very easy with Ed discussion. 
Weaknesses: none
psets were fair and helpful

The course was very well organized, with the topics clearly defined and explained. The teaching team as a whole was very helpful and great teachers. A lot of resources are given for your success in this class. The homeworks and lab sections are really useful for consolidating the learned concepts.

strength - well-designed homeworks and labs, clear that you are being set up for success
weakness - depending on the TF, your section will either be helpful or a waste of time

narratives.question_text: Among the practices in this course geared toward learning during the COVID-19 pandemic, which succeeded and which could be improved? Please comment on course practices that allowed for virtual engagement. (Your anonymous response to this question may be viewed by Yale College students, faculty, and advisers to aid in course selection and evaluating teaching.)
comments: Nothing needs to be improved. The adaptation of this course was perfectly geared towards COVID-19 accommodations.
Everything geared towards COVID was great!
The teaching team was not the most flexible or considerate given the tough semester. They were very communicative, though, and responsive.

Not requiring attendance at lecture would have been helpful, but it did aid engagement. Better recording of lectures would have been helpful, especially because the slideshow was largely absent in the recording. Otherwise, good lectures and the PollEverywhere was great!

Labs should have been recorded. The use of Ed discussion was okay, but it should not have been mandatory to post on there. However, it was wonderful that the course slides were posted to canvas and that PollEverywhere was used to keep engagement consistent.

definitely need to improve the teaching style. reading straight from lecture slides was not beneficial, i did not learn anything during class i spent the whole time rushing to write the notes down before he skipped onto the next slide at super speed
recordings were nice
The recordings were useful when they were posted, and EdDiscussion was a good tool. Virtual sections worked out well.

The pollEv questions during the live lecture were great! Functioning both as active participation and a way for the instructor to gauge students' understanding, I loved being able to do a practice problem or two in the live class so the professor could go over his reasoning for the right answer with all the students present.
I liked the emphasis on live participation and polls. It made the online class seem more personal.

The live lectures were really hard to attend especially since it was during lunch time, so I would have to eat lunch during class and just pay attention to get the required attendance questions - it seemed meticulous and unhelpful. Recorded review sections and lectures helped so much especially when tests came around. EdDiscussion was probably the most useful resource because it helped clarify questions after especially when we were too nervous to do it in a class setting, but the required number just clouded up the forum with useless questions.
I think that the professor could have been easier on students in terms of attendance and participation as the class did take place over zoom and we are under the circumstances of a pandemic.

I think it was overall successful - the live lecture participation requirement certainly made for a more engaging learning experience. The lab sections were very useful to delve deeper into the material and answer questions. Since this was a course in computing and statistics, the remote format worked quite well
Recorded lab sections would be nice
I liked how the lectures were live to make it more engaging but were also recorded because this was very helpful to go back to when studying for exams.
Great job using Polleverywhere and screensharing for office hours and section labs. Edpuzzle was INCREDIBLY helpful!!!!
Prof. Yildirim always monitored the chat well, which was really helpful.

I think that the class did very well overall with virtual engagement. The only thing I would say is that sometimes there was a delay in posting lecture recordings online but this is completely understandable.
Ed discussion was so incredibly helpful, because a lot of the questions I had were shared by others. Recorded lectures were not too helpful, as the recordings did not have the slides in view.

The PSETs and discussion sections were very helpful and succeeded. Additionally, the recorded lectures allowed students to go back and touch up on any concepts that were unfamiliar. The Pollev questions were very helpful as they provided a way to gauge our understanding of the material. The first midterm was very brutal for the class, but the final did fix a lot of the complaints. I do hope the final grade accounts for the issues of midterm 1 as that exam did not accurately represent our knowledge of the course material.
I think everything worked well!
I liked the use of poll everywhere to reinforce what we were learning,

Ed Discussion allowed for people to ask and answer any questions we had about the course and was accessible to everyone. Answering Poll Everywhere questions during lecture contributed toward participation and made lectures more engaging. The use of the chat function on Zoom also allowed for engagement and to ask questions live.

The recordings for the lectures do not show the slides. The Host may have to record the lecture in order for the slides to appear. Ed Discussion made asking questions and getting answers very easy. 

The teaching team should check to see is there are any problems with qualtrics before administering the test.
labs were hard: not much engagement over zoom
virtual lab sections were difficult bc split screens (zoom and r) made it challenging

The lectures were really well organized and easy to follow. The format of the first online midterm was really bad (qualtrics survey), which made the exam quite a stressful experience (also the timing is extremely limited). Thankfully the format was changed for the second midterm (gradescope), although I think the time allotted was quite short for the number of questions. 

Using EdDiscussion was very helpful, as it allowed us to ask questions about anything related to statistics and get input from both our peers and the teaching team in a quite efficient way.

narratives.question_text:
Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
(Your anonymous response to this question may be viewed by Yale College students, faculty, and advisers to aid in course selection and evaluating teaching.)
comments: yes
yes!
Yes! This is a great introductory statistics course which allows you to explore other methods of modeling such as R Studio that you would not have previously learned prior to taking this course.
Yes, great teaching staff.
Yes! I took this course because I wanted to become a more thoughtful consumer and reader, and the course definitely helped me become more confident in statistical models.
If you need a QR credit and are in the social sciences, definitely take this class! It's not necessarily a gut but its manageable and offers stats skills helpful in real life.
Yes. It's a good stats course for psych students, not too difficult, and gives you everything you need to know (pretty much) for understanding (and writing) good psych papers.
Yes. This class was not set up incredibly for COVID, but I do believe that it covered a lot of relevant content and teaches you how to use many important tools
no i did not like this course or the teaching style. maybe with another professor

You are probably looking at this course because you need it for PSYC or CogSci or something, and if it fulfills a major requirement its not that bad. I wouldnt particularly recommend it however if you just need a QR credit, unless you really want to learn about psyc stats and R for some reason (but you may get more out of other S&DS courses)
Yeah it's pretty good

I would recommend this course for any psych majors/cog sci majors (even if it is not required for the major) because of the foundational basic tools it provides you in order to succeed in future research.
if you're a psych major or interested in stats yes. also i think its a pretty interesting and useful QR, just make sure you take it with friends

Yes! If you need an intro to statistics / haven't taken statistics in high school and are looking for a course with approachable content that will probably be useful to you (ie being familiar with R), this course is great!
Yes! I think this course does a great job introducing students to statistics and coding. It is also great that no experience is necessary, and I still feel like I learned quite a bit.
Yes! Very well taught and well organized. Feel confident using and navigating R and understanding basic statistics.

If you have any prior knowledge of stats at all, I would take the higher level class, especially if you need to learn RStudio significantly for a lab. It's a great 5th class though or for the QR credit if you just need it, but I wish I took 230 with my friends because sometime this class felt like a waste since I had already taken AP Stats.
If you have experience with statistics and R, then this class will not be a problem for you. It will be challenging for those like me who had no prior background.
Yes, especially if you are a Psychology major, but also if you are interested in learning the basics of statistics without getting too deep into the CS side of it
Yes. Well structured. Good for beginners
Yes, this course is a psych major req first of all but would be good for anyone wanting to learn important concepts behind statistics and get a basic handle on R programming.
Yes, learning statistics and how data is managed is very important, especially if you are going into the psych field!
Yes!
Yes, great stats course
Yes, it's a good intro to stats.

I would definitely recommend this to other students, especially those that do not feel as confident about quantitative/math related subjects. It was both approachable and challenging and I feel a lot more confident about statistics going forward.
Yes, overall I found this to be an enjoyable course that was a great intro to statistics for someone who had never studied it before.
Yes, I would recommend this course to another student as the information learned can greatly aid your understanding of statistics and research practices.
Yes. You learn a lot about how to read and analyze data, and this knowledge comes in handy when reading news, research papers, etc.
Yes, I think it offers a good foundation in statistics and the courseload is manageable
I would recommend this course. It gives a good overview for stats and R.
If you are taking it as a requirement or are looking for an introductory statistics course

Yes, I would recommend this course more strongly to people who have not taken AP STAT. The first half of the course is almost identical to AP Stat. This course does well to solidify basic concepts and was a great introduction to learning R and applying tests to the real world.
Yes. It's a great QR, a fair class, and Ilker is a fantastic professor.
Yes!!! The course is very well organized and the teaching team is great. Professor Yildirim is a very nice person too.
Yes, it's a great intro to stats that will be very useful in reading and actually understanding psych papers.
As far as QRs go, this is not so bad. Especially if you are a psychology major, it will not be as tough to get through as you think!
